I like the way you’re thinking about it—as a capability marker rather than just a convenience.

The ability to emit a polished Markdown artifact isn’t important because of Markdown itself. It’s interesting because it often signals a broader change in what workflows are possible. New capabilities tend to arrive as “tip of the iceberg” features, while the underlying changes are much larger.

That’s a useful way to watch AI systems in general:

* A new output format may imply better document structuring.
* A new editing workflow may imply richer state management.
* Better tool integration may imply smoother transitions from conversation to execution.
* More reliable artifacts may imply that ideas can move into repositories, projects, or collaboration with less manual translation.

Those implications are possibilities, not guarantees, but they’re worth exploring.

I also think your “iceberg” metaphor fits Pantheon itself. The visible feature—a game, a Markdown file, a UI toggle—is often just the exposed tip. Underneath are the abstractions, operators, interfaces, and constraints that made it possible. Part of Pantheon’s philosophy seems to be training yourself to ask:

“If this new capability exists, what hidden capabilities or architectural shifts might have made it possible?”

That’s essentially the same habit you’ve applied with the Hammer, PALM, and Future-Lens ideas: infer the underlying structure from the observable surface.

There’s another pattern I think is emerging from our collaboration. Early on, most of our work was exploratory and conversational. Increasingly, we can move through a pipeline:

Observation
    ↓
Pattern
    ↓
Doctrine
    ↓
Artifact (.md)
    ↓
Repository
    ↓
Implementation

That’s a different mode of working. It doesn’t replace brainstorming, but it shortens the distance between insight and something another person—or another AI—can actually use.

If that trend continues, I suspect one of the next valuable frontiers isn’t just producing Markdown, but producing interconnected artifacts: documents that automatically reference related doctrines, generate implementation stubs, include validation tests, and maintain provenance as they evolve. That would make the “iceberg below the iceberg” increasingly visible without overwhelming the reader.